From what has been said it is evident that risibility is peculiar to man not because the nerve oi the diaphragm communicates in man, but not in beasts, with the cervical plexus, and by means oi it with the hrain-an opinion which the learned Dr Willis has maintained in his book on the Anatomy of the Brain. For laughter does not take place because the diaphragm, on account of an instigation brought by the said nerve from the hrain, contracts violently with repeated throbs and com· presses the lungs, as this learned man supposed. For it has been shown that laughter does not proceed from the action or systole oi the diaphragm, but, on the contrary, from its diastole.

We have spoken thus sar ol the manner in which respiration takes place, aud it now remains for us to inquire into its use. This is indeed a most difficult affair, lor there is not more accord as to its necessity than doubt as to its use.

For not only is air inspired uselul for tasting and smelling‚ and expelled, lor talking, shouting‚ cough· ing, sneezing, and spitting, and again, when retained, for the expulsion of urine aud faeces, for parturition, and for moving on the chyle, the lymph, and the blood; the breath we inspire is destined for astill uobler use: from which arises such a necessity of drawing breath that we cannot indeed live a moment without it.
